03486nam a22005895i 9780823293124DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232931247 a10.1515/97808232931242doi  a(DE-B1597)566019  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0041202bisacsh1 aFarbman, Herschel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Other Night :bDreaming, Writing, and Restlessness in Twentieth-Century Literature /cHerschel Farbman. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (162 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Other Night -- t1. The Dream as Writing: Freud’s Theory -- t2. Dream and Writing in Blanchot -- t3. Beckett’s Restlessness -- t4. Finnegans Wake -- tAfterword: The Dream and Writing of Socrates -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"I sleep, but my heart wakes," says the Song of Songs. "The other night" names the sleepless night we spend in dreams. From The Interpretation of Dreams to Finnegans Wake, many of the great writing projects of the first half of the twentieth century articulate experiences of waking in the very depths of sleep, where no "I" can declare itself present though the heart still beats. After World War II, in the cold light of the closure of the age of dreambooks, Beckett and Blanchot discover with new clarity, and new fatigue, that what wakes when the "I" sleeps doesn't sleep when the "I" wakes. Revisiting Freud's argument that the dream is a form of writing, The Other Night looks at how life becomes literature in this wakefulness. Though we seem to be seeing things in our dreams, we are actually confronted with a kind of writing. This writing is not in our power, and yet it is ours. We are responsible for it in the same strange way that we are responsible for our lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823293124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823293124/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK